{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"259a00c7-cc04-4106-a605-3feff727aa31","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_JGBnwyg4ZEV4BllEw02XEx","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-18d53cfea3c34796998b1b003f2e348f"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-18d53cfea3c34796998b1b003f2e348f."}],"interactionId":"6b378c0c-c3d8-4b82-917a-8af55b2388e5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nKey issues I see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not required but highly recommended for validation.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet package templates to group related templates.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of the same template exist.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n5. **`defaultValue` references `net9.0`** — This is fine as .NET 9 exists.\n\n\n6. **No `replaces` for Framework symbol** — The `Framework` parameter won't actually substitute into project files without this, which is a functional bug that prevents the selected framework from being applied to the output.\n7. **Missing `postActions`** — Not strictly required but often needed for tasks like restoring NuGet packages.\n\nThe critical blocker here is that the Framework symbol lacks a `replaces` property, so users can select a framework but it won't actually get applied anywhere. Everything else is either recommended for better UX or nice-to-have polish.\n\nThe `sourceName` property does handle project name and namespace replacement, but without seeing the actual template files, I can't confirm whether the .csproj has hardcoded framework values that need swapping. I should check if there are other files in the working directory that are part of this template package.","outputTokens":566,"requestId":"403A:2AE020:480200:54344D:69F005C0"},"id":"986b0fbd-c18b-4be8-